6. "What Am I Missing?" (Updated)
New blind spots in v2:

Operational runbook gap. You have Alert → Case → Board → Lane lifecycle, but no "here's what to do about it" runbook attached to each alert type. An alert without a remediation procedure is just noise.

Alert fatigue is now architecturally embedded. 8 alert category/workflow views + boards + lanes + history + diagnostics. The UI complexity will cause operators to ignore alerts entirely. You need an "Alert Health" metric: noise ratio, MTTR, alert-to-action conversion rate.

Decision Workspace overhead. The formal brief → evidence → action pipeline adds 2-3 clicks before any data appears. For a DBA in a 2am incident, this is unacceptable. You need a "panic mode" that bypasses the decision workspace and goes straight to data.

Codebase bus factor. 293 files, 64K lines of section code, 8-file decision framework, 16 alert center files. If you leave this project, nobody else can maintain it. There's no architecture document, no onboarding guide, no module dependency map.

Session state fragility. The number of st.session_state keys across 293 files is likely >200. One key collision or stale state bug will produce impossible-to-reproduce UI glitches. No evidence of session state schema validation.

Performance ceiling. Streamlit reruns the entire script on every interaction. With 64K lines of section code, even with lazy imports, the framework overhead grows linearly with complexity. You're approaching the point where Streamlit itself becomes the bottleneck.

