What I Genuinely Dislike (Updated)
Everything from v1 still stands. Additionally:

The codebase is growing without discipline. +93 files in one iteration without consolidating existing debt. The Alert Center went from a medium-value list page to a 16-file mini-application. The question is not "can we add more features" but "should we?" Each file added without tests is a future liability.

The Decision Workspace is an inner platform. You've built a framework-within-a-framework: Streamlit → OVERWATCH shell → Decision Workspace (bootstrap, controls, fixtures, scope, state, performance, view model, target filters). This is the classic "inner platform effect" anti-pattern. The formality doesn't help users — it helps the developer maintain consistency. But the developer could achieve consistency with simpler patterns.

Feature breadth is outpacing depth quality. You now have Boards, Lanes, Cases, Signals, Heatmaps, Advisors, Reconciliation, Hierarchy, Diagnostics — but none of these appear to have the polish or completeness that makes a single feature genuinely excellent. I'd rather have 3 world-class features than 15 half-built ones.

The production readiness score went down. That's a bad sign. You shipped features but didn't shore up the foundation. Dynamic tables, tests, removing hardcoded config, securing PII in source code — these are debt items that compound with every feature addition.

293 files with one developer is unsustainable. If this is a solo project, you've crossed the threshold where cognitive load exceeds what a single person can maintain safely. Bugs will emerge from interactions between files you haven't looked at in weeks. The lack of tests makes this inevitable rather than possible.

Bottom line: The v2 update shows genuine architectural ambition and feature depth that would impress in a demo. But it's growing into an application that needs a team, a test suite, and an infrastructure layer (dynamic tables, Native App, CI/CD) — and it doesn't have any of those yet. The gap between "impressive demo" and "production platform" widened in this iteration, not narrowed.
